The paper proposes a new method for segmenting data drawn from sequentially ordered subspaces, which involves finding a sparse representation with an additional penalty term. This problem formulation is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), computer vision (cs.CV), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE). Given that the paper applies its method to various types of data, including infrared hyperspectral, video, and motion capture data, it could potentially fit into any of these sub-categories. However, the focus on segmentation and clustering suggests that cs.LG and cs.CV are the most likely sub-categories, followed by cs.DS, cs.AI, and cs.NE.
